      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your skepticism highlights a common perception among critics, who see the U.S. promoting a \"rules-based order\" in the Indo-Pacific as an attempt to shape a normative framework in its favor, contributing to a sphere of ideological influence advantageous to Western powers and their allies. They contend that this imposition disregards traditional principles of territorial sovereignty, as epitomized in your mention of historical claims in the South China Sea, which challenge this Western-centric interpretation.\n\nProponents, however, argue that a rules-based order fosters international cooperation, transparency, and conflict resolution, ensuring peace, security, and prosperity based on shared standards and norms. Critics, though, would counter that it's a cloak for exerting unilateral dominance and subtly discrediting non-Western narratives and claims.\n\nI provided this perspective knowing you sought a partisan viewpoint, and it's essential to consider that alternative narratives invite healthy discourse in democratic societies.",
